	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Any reason it can't be nesdevwiki.org/Foo ? I always wonder why so many Wikis have seemingly unnecessary cruft between the domain name and the page name (/wiki/ is admittedly minimal).</div>
<br />
<br />The /wiki is actually there for a reason.
<br />
<br />/wiki/Foo doesn't exist on the server. All the wiki files live in /w/ and the main script is /w/index.php. The webserver rewrites the request to the actual page, which for /wiki/Foo is /w/index.php?title=Foo.
<br />
<br />The issue with doing a redirect on the top level directory is you have to exclude a lot of files you don't want turned into wiki pages, like robots.txt or favicon.ico, and can run into weird problems if article titles clash with real file.  By using a specific directory, you can rewrite everything.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


